2 Cluster identification

EconGeo package is a collection of functions used frequently in economic geography related research.

‘hun-patents.csv’ contains data on the number of patents in 4-digit technology classes in Hungarian regions along 2001-2010

‘reg_code’ - NUTS3 codes of Hungarian regions
‘prio_year’ - patent application year
‘tech’ - 4-digit technology class
‘nr_patents’ - number of patents

The aim is to identify clusters based on patents filed between 2006-2010 in Bács-Kiskun county and in Győr-Moson-Sopron county. After we reveal comparative advantages of these counties, check the overlap of concentrated technologies between the two regions.

# import patent data
pat_df <- data.frame(read.csv('hun-patents.csv', header = TRUE, sep=';'))
print(head(pat_df))
##   reg_code prio_year tech nr_patents

## 3    HU101      2001 A23L          1
## 4    HU101      2001 A47J          1
## 5    HU101      2001 A61B          2
## 6    HU101      2001 A61K         14
# filter the data by years and sum up patents by technology and region
pat_df2010 <- pat_df %>%
  filter(prio_year >= 2006 & prio_year <= 2010) %>%
  select(-prio_year) %>%
  group_by(reg_code, tech) %>%
  summarize(nr_patents = sum(nr_patents))
# create a matrix where rows are regions and columns are technologies

4 ERGMs

Exponential Random Graph Models (ERGMs) are quite complicated (see related lecture), but their estimation in R is relative easy! In the following we will do some basic modeling to see whether spinoff companies form more ties in cluster networks, while we control for firm level, dyadic and structural characteristics at the same time.

‘network_data.csv’ is a matrix that represents the knowledge network of firms in the printing and paper product cluster of Kecskemét (in 2012).
‘firm_properties.csv’ contains information on companies in the network.
‘geo_prox_matrix.csv’ is a matrix that represents the geographical proximity of firms in the cluster. (It is measured as the distance of the selected pair of firms subtracted from the maximum physical distance between firms in the cluster.)

We will use the statnet package to estimate ERGMs. Let’s dot it!

First, import the necessary firm level data!

# import properties data

Before we do any estimations, please set the seed for reproducability.

# seed for random network generation
set.seed(10)

We begin with a simple model, containing only two term. By the ergm-term edges we control for the total number of edges in the network. Additionally, we also control for the experience of companies by nodecov(‘experience’).

# check the variable 'experience'
summary(prop$years_in_industry)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2.00   10.00   16.50   14.04   19.00   23.00
# estimate a simple model with edges and experience
model01 <- ergm(knet ~ edges + nodecov('experience'))

Wow, great! We estimated an ERGM!
And yes, there is a significant positive experience effect on the probability of a tie. This means that experienced firms are more connected than they would be in random network settings.

How do we interpret the coefficients here? Note that the experience effect operates on both nodes in a dyad. The conditional log-odds of a tie between two actors is:
−1.21 × change in the number of ties + 0.02 × experience of node A + 0.02 × experience of node B
−1.21 × change in the number of ties + 0.02 × the sum of the experience of the two nodes
For a tie between two nodes with minimum experience, the conditional log-odds is:
−1.21 + 0.02 * (2 + 2) = -1.13
For a tie between two nodes with maximum experience:
−1.21 + 0.02 * (23 + 23) = -0.29
For a tie between a node with maximum experience and a node with minimum experience:
−1.21 + 0.02 * (23 + 2) = -0.71
The corresponding probabilities are 0.24, 0.43, and 0.33. (as exp(-1.13)/(1+exp(-1.13)) = 0.24, …)

If you are interested in the maths behind interpretation in various model settings, please visit http://statnet.org/Workshops/ergm_tutorial.html

So far so good! Now also add controls for employment, external knowledge ties, ownership and spinoff background.
Note, that we used ‘nodecov’ to include a node level continous variable to our model. BUT - there are many different terms to add further variables to ERGMs - see help(“ergm-terms”).

# estimate model02
model02 <- ergm(knet ~ edges + nodecov('spinoff')
                + nodematch('ownership') # group homophily
                + nodecov('experience')
                + nodecov('external_links')
                + nodecov('ln_emp'))

While experience is not significant in this setting, spinoff background seems to influence network ties of companies significantly.
We can use ‘nodematch’ to control for group homophily. It means that we control for whether ties are formed more likely inside groups than they would randomly. In our case ownership group homophily (in terms of foreign-owned and domestic companies) is actually the strongest explanatory factor. It suggests that foreign-owned firms are more likely to share knowledge with other foreign-owned firms, while domestic companies most likely collaborate with other domestic companies.

It is all very cool, but maybe structural features are more important for network tie formation than firm properties.
In the following model we introduce network effects such as GWESP and GWDSP to control for triads and indirect relationships.
GWESP - Geometrically weighted edgewise shared partner distribution - it counts the number of common third partners for each i,j connected nodes. It reflect on the tendency to form triads in the network.
GWDSP - Geometrically weighted dyad-wise shared partners - it counts the number of common third partners for each i,j dyads, that are not connected directly. It measures the extent to which nodes are not directly linked to each other, being at least indirectly linked.
Both variables are great for the aims of ERGMs, but in most cases their parameters should be manually set. This means a lot of trial and error, but at least the models usually converge well!

See an example where we do not set GWESP and GWDSP manually.

# estimate model03A
model03A <- ergm(knet ~ edges + nodecov('spinoff')
                + nodematch('ownership') # group homophily
                + nodecov('experience')
                + nodecov('external_links')
                + nodecov('ln_emp')
                + gwesp(fixed=FALSE) + gwdsp(fixed=FALSE))

# estimate model03A
model03B <- ergm(knet ~ edges + nodecov('spinoff')
                + nodematch('ownership') # group homophily
                + nodecov('experience')

The above model shows that spinoff background and ownership group homophily are still significantly influence knowledge network formation.
Additionally, closed triads (GWESP) are more likely than we would expect by chance, while indirect connections (GWDSP) are significantly less likely than they would be randomly.

We can use AIC and BIC to compare models. Controlling for triads and indirect connections improved the model a lot in comparison to model02.
GREAT!
BUT - how do we know that our estimation is precise and the simulated random networks have the same features as our observed network?
Check Goodness-of-fit (GOF)!

# setup a 2 panel plot
par(mfrow=c(1,2)) 

# comparison in terms of edgewise shared partners and distance in networks
model_gof <- gof(model03B ~ espartners + distance)
plot(model_gof)

As the above figures show the observed network is quite different from the simulated graphs. Our models do not perform well enough at this stage.

Another important thing to check in order to fix our estimations and improve the goodness-of-fit is MCMC diagnostics. When dyad dependent terms are in the model, it is important to assess model convergence before evaluating statistical significance, interpreting coefficients, or assessing goodness of fit. MCMC diagnostics plots how the Markov Chain Montre Carlo process behind random network generation went down.

# run mcmc diagnostics
mcmc.diagnostics(model03B)

## MCMC diagnostics shown here are from the last round of simulation, prior to computation of final parameter estimates. Because the final estimates are refinements of those used for this simulation run, these diagnostics may understate model performance. To directly assess the performance of the final model on in-model statistics, please use the GOF command: gof(ergmFitObject, GOF=~model).

What the above figures show is statistics from the final iteration of the MCMC chain, on the left as a “traceplot” (the deviation of the statistic value in each sampled network from the observed value), and on the right as the distribution of the sample statistic deviations. This is what you want to see in the MCMC diagnostics: the MCMC sample statistics are varying randomly around the observed values at each step (so the chain is “mixing” well), the sampled values show little serial correlation and the difference between the observed and simulated values of the sample statistics have a roughly bell-shaped distribution, centered at 0.
By trial and error you can improve the MCMC process, which will also impact your goodness-of-fit! This is the difficult and time consuming part of ERGMs.
(It is usually the best to begin with the fixed parameters of GWESP and GWDSP.)

One more thing! We discussed on most lectures that geographical proximity matters. How can we control for the influence of geographical proximity on tie formation?

# import the geographic proximity matrix
geoprox <- as.matrix(read.csv("geo_prox_matrix.csv", sep=";", header=TRUE, row.names = 1))

# create a network!
geo_network <- as.network(geoprox, directed = TRUE)

# add edge values to geo_network
set.edge.value(geo_network, "geoprox", geoprox)

As ‘geo_network’ and ‘knet’ consist of the same nodeset, we can use the edge weight of geo_network to explain edges in knet.

# estimate model03A
model04 <- ergm(knet ~ edges + nodecov('spinoff')
                + nodematch('ownership') # group homophily
                + nodecov('experience')
                + nodecov('external_links')
                + nodecov('ln_emp')
                + gwesp(0.2, fixed=TRUE) + gwdsp(1, fixed=TRUE)
                + edgecov(geo_network, "geoprox"))
